verb (used with object), ap·peased, ap·peas·ing.

to satisfy, allay, or relieve; assuage: The fruit appeased his hunger.

posts.subject: I just don't understand the Trump people.
posts.body:
Why would anyone concentrate their efforts on the already converted? It's bizarre, and it makes Trump look like "any other politician".

Seems to me that if Trump had half a brain - he would demand that campaign staff bring him only "fence sitters". Someone who might actually be swayed and still in play?

Those might be hard to find now, with everyone doubling down on their dogma....but they still do exist. And finding people like that is a campaign manager's job.

I watched Bannon once wade into a very hostile crowd to debate Atlantic's CEO. He was hissed and booed. But at the end of that hour - he had really swayed that crowd. They might not have agreed with him - but they respected him. And it was clear the crowd was willing to listen to him further.

Swaying a hostile crowd is not easy. But it's something Trump must master. He needs to get out of his bubble.

I think citizens yearn for politicians who will quit pandering and speak truth.

This Tulsa gathering? Just a waste. Someone should have been fired over that.

posts.subject: I favor ruthless observance of property rights.
posts.body:
If Facebook, Twitter, Reddit don't want you to post - it should be their right to censor. Meanwhile, the government is permanently restrained from ALL censorship.

Still, I do see problems with this view. primarily continuity. We must carve out a space where neutral ground exists (like libraries).

If we lose the internet archive wayback machine - the loss to the public will be great.
